ual report from my children's school, and noticed that they have changed the RE aspect of education a little...I'm always trying to explain to people how they teach religion in English schools, so I thought that I'd copy the info here, for anyone who is interested. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
&quot;The syllabus for Religious Education requires schools to teach a broadly Christian curriculum and, additionally, certain aspects of Judaism and Hinduism.  Sometimes a &quot;themed&quot; approach to learning is used.  Fore example, the festivals of Hannukkah and Diwali link well with Christian festivals connected with light.&quot;<br>
<br>
So there you go - that is basically how it is done...they have a Christian assembly every morning, for a &quot;collective act of worship&quot;, and everything throughout the school is taught from a Christian perspective, with the addition of learning about different religions (with the emphasis on the fact that they aren't what &quot;we&quot; believe), at different times of the year. <br>
<br>
