<br>
Basically, if you have a recognised religious belief that differs from mainstream xianity - you are allowed to keep your children out of the assemblies (they go to the book corner and read usually). <br>
<br>
We have a lot of Church of England schools which are more religious than the &quot;normal&quot; schools (like the one my children are at)..they do a lot more RE - and we also have private schools where xianity is really pushed (or whatever religion it was set up for...but like I said, I think there is only one muslim school)...<br>
<br>
As distressing as it sounds, my childrens school is actually pretty laid back when it comes to religion - they basically teach the minimum they have to by law (although the headmaster is a fundi, so I think he tends to string out the assemblies more than necessary - when parents attend for whatever reason, if they don't sing loud enough, or all bow their heads in prayer, he makes everyone do it again! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).<br>
