A lot of things depend on the family.  I don't agree with the situation that you gave with the gift giving.  I have two daughters from my first marriage and their dad is not a witness.  They go to his house on the holidays just like the divorce papers say, the holidays are split just like in any other divorce. (I was not a witness until after I got divorced.)  My children will be able to decide what they want to do religion wise when they are old enough.  Their dad has every right to take them to church if he wants to when he has them and teach them what he feels is right and when they are at my home they will be taught what I feel is right. No different than if he was catholic or whatever and I was atheist.  In fact, some parents let their kids get baptized when they are 14 or 15 or whatever, but I will be encouraging my kids to wait until they are older like 18 or 19.  My oldest is a people pleaser and I want her to do it(get baptized) for her, and for God, if that is her choice, not for me or her Pops(step-dad).  There is a song that I just love that we sing, it is calles &quot;Make the Truth Your Own&quot; and I think of my kids everytime we sing it.  Also, about the disfellowshipping thing, anyone who is baptized knows going in what happens if you are disfellowshipped.  If anyone knows anyone that is DFed and is mad or upset about it, they knew what would happen.  <br>
