<br>
That's really interesting Trish. Is an unsympathetic &quot;they knew it would happen&quot; approach generally the JW attitude toward the DF'd? It really doesn't allow for the possibility of one having a change of heart, does it? It is normal for people to grow, mature and change. But for JWs, sounds like the consequences of having a change of heart are so brutal that I would think the very spector of DFing would frighten all but the most bold from even the prospect of seriously questioning JW teachings. <br>
<br>
Is there some weakness in the teachings that can't stand up to scrutiny? I can't imagine why else such threat of loss would be needed to keep believers in line.<br>
<br>
I ask because I don't know a lot about JWs but I am applying this to my own experience of Catholic temporary insanity. If Catholics DF'd (or practiced a true excommunication - which they don't really do because church membership = $$$) then my husband and kids would be forbidden to see me?  That's unthinkable.<br>
<br>
When I &quot;went in&quot; I did NOT know I would one day utterly lose my faith. Going in I did not know the future. But if they were threatening to cut me off from my babies, I would have felt pressured to shut down my intellect and pretend to believe.<br>
<br>
How does one choose to submit to a religious authority that would forbid them to see a loved one if either lost faith? Wow. Even prisoners on death row get to see their moms.<br>
<br>
I don't mean you any disrespect Trish. I appreciate your posts. This just struck close to home and I'm having a hard time getting my mind around it.<br>
<br>
DL<br>
